03925nmm a2200565Ia 9781501728747DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20182009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017287477 a10.7591/97815017287472doi  a(DE-B1597)515018  a(OCoLC)1091656038  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY04a973.61 aMcKivigan, John R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe War against Proslavery Religion :bAbolitionism and the Northern Churches, 1830–1865 /cJohn R. McKivigan. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b8 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReflecting a prodigious amount of research in primary and secondary sources, this book examines the efforts of American abolitionists to bring northern religious institutions to the forefront of the antislavery movement.John R. McKivigan employs both conventional and quantitative historical techniques to assess the positions adopted by various churches in the North during the growing conflict over slavery, and to analyze the stratagems adopted by American abolitionists during the 1840s and 1850s to persuade northern churches to condemn slavery and to endorse emancipation. Working for three decades to gain church support for their crusade, the abolitionists were the first to use many of the tactics of later generations of radicals and reformers who were also attempting to enlist conservative institutions in the struggle for social change.To correct what he regards to be significant misperceptions concerning church-oriented abolitionism, McKivigan concentrates on the effects of the abolitionists' frequent failures, the division of their movement, and the changes in their attitudes and tactics in dealing with the churches. By examining the pre-Civil War schisms in the Presbyterian, Baptist, and Methodist denominations, he shows why northern religious bodies refused to embrace abolitionism even after the defection of most southern members. He concludes that despite significant antislavery action by a few small denominations, most American churches resisted committing themselves to abolitionist principles and programs before the Civil War.In a period when attention is again being focused on the role of religious bodies in influencing efforts to solve America's social problems, this book is especially timely.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAbolitionistszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aAntislavery movementszUnited States. 0aSlavery and the church. 4aReligious Studies. 4aSlavery Studies. 4aU.S. History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172874740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501728747423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501728747/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles